Looking at this problem, I need to prove that the center of mass of a solid sphere centered at the origin is 0.

The key insight is that the integral of the position vector over a ball centered at the origin is 0 by symmetry - for every point x in the ball, -x is also in the ball, so they cancel out.

```lean
/-- The center of mass of a solid sphere located at the origin is `0`. -/
lemma solidSphere_centerOfMass {d : ℕ} (m R : ℝ≥0) (hr : R ≠ 0) :
    (solidSphere d.succ m R).centerOfMass = 0 := by
  simp only [centerOfMass, solidSphere]
  simp only [Nat.succ_eq_add_one, LinearMap.coe_mk, AddHom.coe_mk]
  have h : ∫ x in Metric.closedBall (0 : Space d.succ) R, x ∂volume = 0 := by
    apply integral_eq_zero_of_neg_eq
    intro x
    simp only [Metric.mem_closedBall, dist_zero_right, neg_neg, norm_neg]
  simp only [h, smul_zero]
```
